{
  "id": "recursive",
  "name": "Recursive Pricing",
  "desc": "Derived outputs become inputs for the next generation, so pricing based on first use misses the compounding value. The original price structure cannot capture value chains it did not anticipate, and renegotiation lags behind the recursion.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Tool-grade",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing typically involves tool-grade models whose outputs are commercially valuable enough to feed back into production pipelines as inputs.",
      "detail": "The model must be capable enough to produce outputs with standalone commercial value. Narrow models rarely generate outputs worth reusing. Tool-grade capability is the threshold where derived outputs become commercially interesting inputs. The recursive pricing problem does not arise until the model's outputs are good enough to substitute for or enhance the original licensed data."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "Multi-domain",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing problems intensify across multiple domains because derived outputs from one domain become inputs for models in another domain.",
      "detail": "Cross-domain value chains create recursive loops that single-domain pricing cannot capture. A model trained on financial data produces analytics that improve healthcare research, which generates insights feeding back into financial modelling. Multi-domain breadth multiplies the recursive paths. Pricing structures designed for one domain cannot track value as it crosses domain boundaries."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Rapid",
      "memo": "Rapid capability improvement accelerates recursive pricing failure because each model generation produces higher-quality outputs that are more valuable as inputs.",
      "detail": "As models improve, their outputs become better substitutes for original training data. Rapid trajectory means pricing agreements negotiated for one capability level become inadequate as the model improves. The gap between contracted price and actual value widens with each capability jump. Pricing structures cannot keep pace with capability trajectories that compress improvement into months."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "AI-assisted",
      "memo": "AI-assisted research accelerates the discovery of new derived-value pathways, revealing recursive pricing gaps faster than commercial teams can renegotiate terms.",
      "detail": "AI tools identify patterns in data that humans would miss, including unexpected correlations between datasets that create new derived-value opportunities. AI-assisted research means the model itself helps discover why the pricing is wrong. This self-revealing quality of AI research creates a feedback loop where capability improvement exposes pricing inadequacy. Research automation compounds the recursive problem."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-call enabled",
      "memo": "Tool-call-enabled models can chain outputs through multiple processing steps, creating derived-value pathways that simple inference models cannot produce.",
      "detail": "Tool-call capability allows the model to query databases, run analyses, and combine results in multi-step workflows. Each step can produce derived outputs with independent commercial value. The pricing structure may cover the initial query but not the derived chain. Tool-call enablement is where recursive value creation begins to outrun linear pricing structures."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Many copies",
      "memo": "Many model copies across an organisation multiply the recursive pricing problem because each copy independently generates derived outputs that feed back into the system.",
      "detail": "Each deployed copy produces outputs that can enter the organisation's data pipeline. Many copies running simultaneously create parallel derived-value streams that compound. The pricing structure accounts for one model's usage but not for the system-level effect of many copies generating reusable outputs. Scale magnifies the gap between contracted price and actual value extraction."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Faster-than-human",
      "memo": "Faster-than-human processing speed means the model generates derived outputs faster than commercial teams can track value creation or update pricing terms.",
      "detail": "Machine-speed output generation outpaces the human commercial cycle of recognition, negotiation, and contract amendment. By the time a pricing gap is identified, the model has already produced millions of derived outputs. Speed asymmetry is structural: the model creates value at machine speed while contracts update at human speed. This temporal mismatch is core to recursive pricing failure."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing is a cognitive and commercial problem rather than a physical-world issue, arising from how data and model outputs flow through digital value chains.",
      "detail": "The recursion happens in data pipelines and analytical workflows, not in physical systems. Cognitive outputs become cognitive inputs. The value chain is entirely digital and informational. Physical-world extension would add complexity but the recursive pricing problem is already fully present in the cognitive domain. The challenge is tracking value through digital derivation chains."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Copilot/worker",
      "memo": "The model operates as a copilot or worker producing substantial analytical outputs that users then incorporate into further work, creating the derivation chains that break.",
      "detail": "Copilot-level integration means the model's outputs are substantive contributions to the user's work product. Unlike informational tools whose outputs are consumed and forgotten, copilot outputs are incorporated, saved, and reused. Worker-level production creates artifacts with independent commercial value. The role determines whether outputs accumulate as reusable assets or dissipate as consumed information."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Informational",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing involves informational outputs whose value compounds through reuse, not through the model taking binding actions in external systems.",
      "detail": "The model produces information: analyses, predictions, summaries, and synthetic data. Each informational output can become an input for the next processing cycle. Informational actuation is where recursive value creation is purest because information can be copied and reused without degradation. The non-rivalrous nature of informational output is what enables the recursive loop."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Human-in-loop",
      "memo": "Human users in the loop select which model outputs to retain and reuse, inadvertently creating the curated derived datasets that compound recursive value.",
      "detail": "Human curation adds value to model outputs by selecting the best, correcting errors, and combining results. This human-curated selection process transforms raw model outputs into high-quality derived data. The human in the loop does not intend to create a recursive pricing problem but their curation labour makes derived outputs more valuable than raw model outputs. Human selection is an unrewarded value-add."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "Recommend only",
      "memo": "The model recommends analyses and outputs that human users then choose to incorporate into production workflows, creating derived assets through human-mediated selection.",
      "detail": "Recommendation authority means the model suggests but humans decide. Each human decision to incorporate a recommendation into production work creates a derived artifact. The recommendation role masks the value creation: the model's contribution appears advisory but its outputs become permanent production assets. Recommend-only authority does not prevent recursive value accumulation."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Gated tools",
      "memo": "Gated tool access allows the model to query data sources and run analyses within controlled boundaries, but each tool interaction can produce derived outputs with.",
      "detail": "Each gated tool interaction produces results that may be more valuable than the inputs. A model querying a licensed database produces analytical outputs that the database licence may not have priced for. Gated access controls which tools the model reaches but does not control the value of what comes back. The pricing gap sits at the boundary between input access and output value."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
      "value": "Manual stop",
      "memo": "Manual intervention can stop the model from producing more derived outputs, but value already created through recursive derivation cannot be recalled or unpriced.",
      "detail": "Stopping future production does not address the value already extracted through recursive derivation. Manual stop is a forward-looking control that cannot retroactively correct pricing failures. By the time someone identifies the recursive pricing problem, the derived value has already accumulated. Manual stop is the available intervention but it arrives too late to prevent the pricing gap."
    },
    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "Enterprise",
      "memo": "Enterprise-level users deploy models at scale where recursive pricing failures become material commercial issues affecting contract economics and supplier relationships.",
      "detail": "Enterprise deployment creates the volume where recursive pricing becomes significant. Individual users producing occasional derived outputs do not create material pricing gaps. Enterprise-scale deployment with systematic reuse of model outputs across business units creates compounding value that the input price did not anticipate. Enterprise is the command level where recursive pricing becomes a commercial problem."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
      "memo": "Pricing renegotiations follow product-cycle tempo while recursive value creation operates continuously, ensuring the pricing structure always lags the value reality.",
      "detail": "Commercial contracts renegotiate annually or at renewal. Recursive value creation happens with every model invocation. The tempo mismatch means the pricing structure is always out of date. By the time a pricing review occurs, months of unpriced recursive value creation have already accumulated. Product-cycle tempo is too slow for the continuous value creation that recursive derivation produces."
    },
    "Tradeoff Authority": {
      "value": "Product team",
      "memo": "Product teams make deployment decisions that create recursive value chains without recognising the pricing implications until the commercial team identifies the gap.",
      "detail": "The product team optimises for capability and user experience, not for pricing structure integrity. Decisions to retain model outputs, feed them back as inputs, and build derived datasets are product decisions made without commercial review. Product-team authority over deployment creates the recursive loops. Commercial and legal teams discover the pricing problem after the product architecture has already created it."
    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Purpose-limited",
      "memo": "Purpose-limited permission authorises specific uses of licensed data but does not anticipate that model outputs derived from that data will re-enter the processing pipeline.",
      "detail": "The licence permits using data for defined purposes. Derived outputs from those purposes may not be covered by the original permission. When derived outputs become inputs for the next generation, the purpose chain extends beyond what was licensed. Purpose limitation creates a legal ambiguity: the original use was permitted but the recursive reuse may not be. The permission boundary is where pricing and rights intersect."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Permissive",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing failures thrive in permissive regulatory environments where few constraints exist on how derived outputs can be reused as inputs for further processing.",
      "detail": "Permissive regulation allows derived outputs to flow freely through processing pipelines without regulatory checkpoints. No regulatory requirement forces disclosure of recursive value creation or sharing of derived-output value with original data providers. Permissive posture means the market, not the regulator, must solve recursive pricing. The market has not yet developed pricing mechanisms adequate to the problem."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Licensed",
      "memo": "Licensed data enters the model under pricing terms that assumed one-time processing, not recursive reuse of derived outputs as new training or inference inputs.",
      "detail": "The licence priced the data for its input value, not for the recursive output value the model would generate. Licensed availability creates a contractual relationship that the recursive pricing problem stresses. The data provider licensed access expecting the value to flow one way. Recursive derivation means value flows in circles, and the licence only priced the first pass."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Mixed/declared",
      "memo": "Derived outputs carry mixed provenance because they blend licensed inputs with model processing and prior derived data, making value attribution increasingly difficult.",
      "detail": "Each recursive pass mixes the provenance of original data with model-generated content and previously derived outputs. After several recursion cycles, the contribution of any single original data source becomes untraceable. Mixed provenance is the mechanism that makes recursive pricing intractable: you cannot price what you cannot attribute. Provenance decay accelerates with each derivation layer."
    },
    "Model-Weight Rights": {
      "value": "Hosted only",
      "memo": "The model operates as a hosted service where the processor controls the weights and the recursive value chain, while the data provider has no visibility.",
      "detail": "Hosted-only access means the data provider cannot inspect how their data contributes to the model's outputs or how those outputs re-enter processing pipelines. The processor controls the infrastructure where recursive derivation occurs. Hosted arrangement creates information asymmetry: the processor sees the recursive value while the data provider sees only the input price. Rights without visibility is a structural disadvantage."
    },
    "Territory": {
      "value": "Domestic",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing problems occur within domestic territory where a single legal framework governs but provides no specific mechanism for pricing recursive derivation.",
      "detail": "Domestic scope simplifies the legal analysis but does not solve the pricing problem. A single jurisdiction's contract and intellectual property law applies. However, no established legal doctrine specifically addresses recursive value chains created by AI processing. Domestic territory means the problem is legally coherent but commercially unresolved. Cross-border recursion would add jurisdictional complexity to the pricing problem."
    },
    "Data Subject Exposure": {
      "value": "No personal data",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing is primarily a commercial data problem involving market data, content, and analytics rather than personal data with privacy constraints.",
      "detail": "The recursive pricing problem is cleanest with commercial data where value attribution is the central issue rather than privacy. Market data, content libraries, and analytical datasets are the typical inputs. Personal data would add privacy complications but the recursive pricing problem exists independently of data protection. The commercial dynamics are visible without privacy overlay."
    },
    "Data Sensitivity": {
      "value": "Commercial confidential",
      "memo": "Commercially confidential data creates the sharpest recursive pricing problem because the derived value is commercially significant and the data provider has competitive interest.",
      "detail": "When commercially confidential data enters the model, the derived outputs may contain commercially valuable insights that the data provider did not intend to share. Confidential data creates the highest-stakes recursive pricing problem because the value at stake is competitively significant. The data provider's commercial secrets may be partially reflected in derived outputs that the processor then monetises."
    },
    "Control Exposure": {
      "value": "No control issue",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing is a commercial contract problem that does not typically involve export-controlled technology or government-regulated materials.",
      "detail": "The recursive pricing stance operates in commercial markets where the constraint is contractual pricing, not government control regimes. Export control and classification are not relevant to the core pricing dynamic. The absence of control issues means the problem is purely commercial, making it solvable through contract design if the parties recognise the recursion. No regulatory intervention is needed."
    },
    "Processing Mode": {
      "value": "Training",
      "memo": "Recursive pricing failure is most acute in training because model weights permanently absorb the value of input data, and derived outputs from training feed back.",
      "detail": "Training creates the deepest recursive loop because the model's capabilities permanently reflect the training data. Derived outputs from a trained model can become training data for the next generation. Each training cycle compounds the value extracted from original inputs. Training-mode processing is where pricing failure is most severe because the value absorption is permanent and the recursion is generational."
    },
    "Derivation": {
      "value": "Recursive derivation",
      "memo": "This is the defining dimension: derived outputs become inputs for subsequent processing, creating recursive derivation chains that compound beyond any linear pricing model.",
      "detail": "Recursive derivation is the core mechanism. Model outputs from round one become training data for round two. Round two's outputs feed round three. Each round adds value that the original input price did not capture. The derivation chain can extend indefinitely, with each layer further diluting the provenance of original inputs. Recursive derivation is what makes this pricing problem structurally different from ordinary licensing."
    },
    "Retention / Persistence": {
      "value": "Weight-entangled",
      "memo": "Derived value persists in model weights permanently, meaning the recursive pricing gap compounds with each training generation and cannot be unwound by deleting data.",
      "detail": "Weight entanglement means the value extracted from original data is permanently embedded in the model's capabilities. Deleting the original data does not remove the derived capability. Each recursive training cycle deepens the entanglement. Weight persistence is what makes the recursive pricing problem irreversible: you cannot reprice the past because the value has already been absorbed into the weights."
    },
    "Execution / Residency Environment": {
      "value": "Public cloud",
      "memo": "Public cloud execution enables recursive processing at scale because elastic compute allows continuous derivation without infrastructure constraints slowing the value extraction.",
      "detail": "Cloud infrastructure removes the compute bottleneck that might otherwise limit recursive derivation. The processor can scale derivation pipelines on demand, accelerating value extraction beyond what fixed infrastructure would permit. Public cloud execution makes recursive pricing failure worse by removing the natural throttle of compute scarcity. Unlimited compute means unlimited recursion speed."
    },
    "Boundary": {
      "value": "Shared",
      "memo": "Shared processing boundaries allow derived outputs from one customer's data to influence models that serve other customers, multiplying the recursive value pathways.",
      "detail": "In shared environments, derived outputs from one data provider's licensed data can influence models used by other customers. The value crosses boundaries invisibly. Shared boundaries mean the recursive pricing problem is not contained to a single data provider's contract. Value leaks across all customers in the shared environment. Shared boundaries make individual pricing agreements structurally incomplete."
    },
    "Deployment Surface": {
      "value": "Customer-facing",
      "memo": "Customer-facing deployment means derived outputs reach end users who generate feedback and interaction data that feeds back into the recursive value chain.",
      "detail": "Customer-facing deployment creates the feedback loop that completes the recursive circuit. Users interact with model outputs, generating preference data, corrections, and usage patterns. This interaction data becomes training signal for the next model generation. Customer-facing deployment is where the recursion closes the loop: licensed data produces outputs, outputs generate interactions, interactions become training data."
    },
    "Physical Infrastructure": {
      "value": "Commercial cloud",
      "memo": "Commercial cloud infrastructure enables the processor to scale recursive derivation elastically without the capital constraints that dedicated infrastructure would impose.",
      "detail": "Cloud infrastructure is the enabler of unconstrained recursion. The processor scales compute to maximise derivation throughput. Capital constraints do not limit the speed of recursive value extraction. Commercial cloud makes the economics of recursion favourable for the processor while the data provider's price remains fixed. Infrastructure elasticity amplifies the pricing asymmetry."
    },
    "Model Sourcing": {
      "value": "Single-provider",
      "memo": "Single-provider model sourcing means one processor controls the entire recursive derivation pipeline, concentrating the pricing advantage in one party.",
      "detail": "The single provider trains the model, produces derived outputs, feeds them back as training data, and trains the next generation. The entire recursive loop runs within one organisation's control. Single-provider concentration means no external party has visibility into the recursion. The data provider sees only the input contract while the processor sees the full recursive value chain."
    },
    "Compute Source": {
      "value": "Committed capacity",
      "memo": "Committed compute capacity ensures the processor can sustain continuous recursive derivation without interruption, deepening the pricing gap with each cycle.",
      "detail": "Committed capacity means the processor has guaranteed compute for ongoing training runs. The derivation pipeline runs continuously rather than in sporadic bursts. Committed capacity enables systematic recursive value extraction. The processor's compute commitment is an investment in recursive value capture that the data provider's fixed input price does not reflect."
    },
    "Cloud Dependency": {
