      "memo": "Market access to compute means the processor can scale recursive derivation by purchasing more hardware, with no strategic supply constraints limiting value extraction.",
      "detail": "The processor acquires compute through normal market channels. No strategic gatekeeper limits the processor's ability to scale recursive training. Market access means the speed of recursive value extraction is limited only by the processor's budget, not by supply constraints. The data provider has no leverage through the compute supply chain to slow recursive derivation."
    },
    "Silicon Bottleneck": {
      "value": "Accelerator supply",
      "memo": "Accelerator supply constraints occasionally throttle recursive derivation speed, providing a brief natural brake on the rate of recursive value extraction.",
      "detail": "GPU scarcity can temporarily slow the processor's recursive training pipeline. When accelerator supply tightens, derivation cycles lengthen and fewer recursive rounds occur per period. However, supply constraints are temporary and the processor queues recursive work for execution when capacity becomes available. Accelerator bottlenecks delay but do not prevent recursive pricing failure."
    },
    "Substitutability": {
      "value": "Locked-in",
      "memo": "Data providers become locked in because their data's value has been absorbed into model weights through recursive derivation, making switching or withdrawal meaningless.",
      "detail": "The data provider cannot withdraw meaningfully because their data's contribution is already entangled in model weights across multiple recursive generations. Switching to a different processor does not recall the value already extracted. Lock-in is created not by contract terms but by the irreversible nature of recursive weight entanglement. The data provider is locked into a pricing structure that structurally undervalues their contribution."
    },
    "Vertical Integration": {
      "value": "Stack-integrated",
      "memo": "The processor's stack integration from data ingestion through training to deployment creates a seamless recursive pipeline that the data provider cannot observe or influence.",
      "detail": "Stack integration means the processor controls every stage where recursive value creation occurs. Data ingestion, training, output generation, and output recycling all happen within the processor's integrated stack. The data provider interacts only with the ingestion endpoint. Stack integration makes recursive derivation invisible to external parties and concentrates all derived value within the processor."
    },
    "Distribution Channel": {
      "value": "API/app",
      "memo": "API distribution channels deliver model outputs to customers whose interactions generate feedback data that completes the recursive loop back into training.",
      "detail": "API distribution is the channel through which recursive value creation reaches end users. Each API call produces outputs that may be retained and reused. User interactions through the API generate preference data and corrections. The API channel is both the value-delivery mechanism and the data-collection mechanism that feeds the next recursive cycle. Distribution and data collection are one channel."
    },
    "Supply Jurisdiction": {
      "value": "Domestic",
      "memo": "Domestic supply jurisdiction means the recursive pricing problem operates within a single legal framework that has not yet developed doctrine for recursive value attribution.",
      "detail": "The processor, data provider, and end users operate within one jurisdiction. Domestic scope means contract law and intellectual property doctrines apply consistently but have no specific provisions for recursive AI value chains. No court has established how to price recursive derivation. Domestic jurisdiction provides legal coherence without legal solutions for the novel pricing problem."
    },
    "Observability": {
