      "memo": "The recursive derivation pipeline is opaque to the data provider, who cannot observe how their data's value compounds through successive model generations.",
      "detail": "Opacity is the structural enabler of recursive pricing failure. The data provider cannot see how many derivation rounds have occurred, how their data influenced model capabilities, or how derived outputs feed back as inputs. Without observability, the data provider cannot know the true value of their contribution. Opacity means the data provider prices blind while the processor captures sighted value."
    },
    "Evaluation": {
      "value": "Internal tests",
      "memo": "Model evaluation uses internal tests controlled by the processor, with no external verification of how recursive derivation affects model capability or output quality.",
      "detail": "The processor evaluates its own models against its own benchmarks. No external party verifies how recursive training affects quality or capability. Internal testing means the processor knows the value of recursive derivation while the data provider does not. Evaluation asymmetry mirrors the information asymmetry: the processor has complete visibility while the data provider has none."
    },
    "Interpretability": {
      "value": "Black box",
      "memo": "The model's internal workings are a black box to data providers, making it impossible to trace how original input data contributed to recursively derived outputs.",
      "detail": "Black-box models prevent data providers from understanding how their data influenced the model or its derived outputs. Without interpretability, value attribution is impossible. The data provider cannot demonstrate that the model's capabilities derived substantially from their data. Black-box status protects the processor's information advantage and prevents the data provider from making a credible pricing claim."
    },
    "Alignment Method": {
